{"id": 19800, "date": "2020-08-04T05:00:00", "date_gmt": "2020-08-04T12:00:00", "guid": {"rendered": "http://estreetshuffle.com/?p=19800"}, "modified": "2020-08-02T20:02:06", "modified_gmt": "2020-08-03T03:02:06", "slug": "cover-me-seventh-son", "status": "publish", "type": "post", "link": "https://estreetshuffle.com/index.php/2020/08/04/cover-me-seventh-son/", "title": {"rendered": "Cover Me: Seventh Son"}, "content": {"rendered": "<p>When the Working on a Dream Tour stopped in Greensboro, Bruce honored a sign request from a young boy who, I suspect, had a little bit of prompting from his parents.</p>\n<p>The boy was holding a sign for &#8220;Seventh Son,&#8221; written by Willie Dixon and first recorded by Willie Mabel in 1955 in an R&amp;B arrangement.</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><iframe loading=\"lazy\" title=\"Willie Mabon-The Seventh Son\" width=\"758\" height=\"569\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/6EphtWmrlXg?feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share\" referrerpolicy=\"strict-origin-when-cross-origin\" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n<p>It was Johnny Rivers&#8217; rocking cover of it a decade later that propelled the song into the charts, however&#8211;it spent most of the summer of 1965 on the Billboard Hot 100 chart, where it peaked at #7.</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><iframe loading=\"lazy\" title=\"JOHNNY RIVERS(VIDEO CLIP)-&quot;SEVENTH SON&quot;(LYRICS)\" width=\"758\" height=\"569\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/lRS8FzSuLR8?feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share\" referrerpolicy=\"strict-origin-when-cross-origin\" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n<p>As classic rock songs go, &#8220;Seventh Son&#8221; is a bit on the obscure side, and Bruce was clearly skeptical about where the boy had heard the song.</p>\n<p>But he was also tickled, and never one to back away from a challenge, Bruce gamely rallied the E Street Band for their first and only cover of &#8220;Seventh Son.&#8221;</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><iframe loading=\"lazy\" title=\"Bruce Springsteen Greensboro 5-2-09 7th Son\" width=\"758\" height=\"569\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/YvGzfGxFdjE?feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share\" referrerpolicy=\"strict-origin-when-cross-origin\" allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n<p>(I was fortunate enough to be at that show, in the presence of the best American crowd I&#8217;ve ever seen. For more highlights, see my <a href=\"http://estreetshuffle.com/index.php/2018/05/02/where-the-band-was-greensboro-may-2-2009/\">Where the Band Was report</a> from that night.)</p>\n<p><strong>Seventh Son<br />\nFirst performed:</strong> May 2, 2009 (Greensboro, NC)<br />\n<strong>Last performed:</strong> May 2, 2009 (Greensboro, NC)</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n", "protected": false}, "excerpt": {"rendered": "<p>One time only: Honoring a young fan&#8217;s request (or perhaps his parents&#8217;), Bruce and the E Street Band delivered a crowd-pleasing cover of Johnny Rivers&#8217; 1965 hit.</p>\n", "protected": false}, "author": 1, "featured_media": 20190, "comment_status": "open", "ping_status": "open", "sticky": false, "template": "", "format": "standard", "meta": {"_monsterinsights_skip_tracking": false, "_monsterinsights_sitenote_active": false, "_monsterinsights_sitenote_note": "", "_monsterinsights_sitenote_category": 0, "jetpack_post_was_ever_published": false, "_jetpack_newsletter_access": "", "_jetpack_dont_email_post_to_subs": false, "_jetpack_newsletter_tier_id": 0, "_jetpack_memberships_contains_paywalled_content": false, "_jetpack_memberships_contains_paid_content": false, "footnotes": "", "jetpack_publicize_message": "", "jetpack_publicize_feature_enabled": true, "jetpac